\subsubsection{Introduction}\label{introduction}

This R Markdown document presents the Bellabeat data analysis case study
through the Google Data Analysis Course. In this document, we will
explore the business task that is proposed by Bellabeat, a high-tech
manufacturer of health products for women. Bellabeats aims to increase
their global presence in the smart device market by understanding user
behaviour that can guide product strategies and marketing decisions.

Urška Sršen, cofounder and Chief Creative Officer of Bellabeat, believes
that by analysing existing competitor data (Fitbit) and comparing it to
Bellabeat's Time Product (a wellness watch that tracks users' activity,
sleep, and stress), we can apply existing trends to the device,
benefiting both Bellabeat and helping support their customers better.

\subsubsection{Business Task}\label{business-task}

Sršen has requested an analysis of smart device usage to gain insight
into how customers use non-Bellabeat smart devices.

\begin{enumerate}
\def\labelenumi{\arabic{enumi}.}
\tightlist
\item
  What are some trends in smart device usage?
\item
  How could these trends apply to Bellabeat customers?
\item
  How could these trends help influence Bellabeat's marketing strategy?
\end{enumerate}

\subsubsection{Source}\label{source}

The public dataset was provided by Sršen,
\href{https://www.kaggle.com/datasets/arashnic/fitbit}{FitBit Fitness
Tracker Data}. This dataset is the raw, unedited Kaggle dataset
containing usage data from thirty Fitbit users.

This document will focus mainly on:

\begin{itemize}
\item
  \texttt{dailyActivity\_merged}
\item
  \texttt{sleepDay\_merged}
\item
  \texttt{dailySteps\_merged}
\item
  \texttt{weightLogInfo\_merged}
\end{itemize}

\subsubsection{Data Limitations}\label{data-limitations}

The data itself is presented with a few limitations that are noteworthy.
There are only 30 Fitbit users, which is a relatively small sample. The
data itself does not represent Bellabeats users; this data is only an
implication of what can be applied to them. Some data is self-reported,
such as Weight, which can lead to inconsistencies or incorrect inputs.
Missing some potential information, such as gender and age, which could
have provided more insight. No context of what people do in bed before
they are asleep.

\subsubsection{Cleaning}\label{cleaning}

For the Cleaning of the Data, Google Sheets was used before exporting
the data into R Studio, as the data was not too large and the process
would be quick and fast, leading to a faster response time to the
Stakeholders' Business Task.

The following is a breakdown of key cleaning that was conducted on
Google Sheets.

\begin{itemize}
\item
  Standardised date format from \texttt{MM/DD/YYYY} to
  \texttt{YYYY/MM/DD}, allowing data to be consistent and universally
  readable.
\item
  Applied filter to \texttt{sleepDay\_merged} Column D, Sort A-Z,
  applied syntax in column G
  \texttt{=IF(COUNTIFS(D:D,\ D2,\ E:E,\ E2)\ \textgreater{}\ 1,\ "Duplicate",\ "Unique")}.
  Showing duplicates, Applied Data cleanup to remove the duplicates. 3
  data entries removed from \texttt{sleepDay\_merged}. Other data
  entries returned results of no duplicates.
\item
  Applied conditional formatting to see if any empty cells, removed
  Column \texttt{Fat} from \texttt{weightLogInfo\_merged}, as there were
  only 2 completed entries.
\item
  Removed non-representative days in \texttt{dailySteps\_merged} where
  \texttt{StepTotal} \textless{} 50 steps, as these days were days of
  inactivity of the Fitbit by users.
\item
  Applied \texttt{=IF(SUM(C2:M2)=0,\ "Non-Wear",\ "Valid")} to
  \texttt{DailyActivity\_merged} to determine exactly which days had no
  activity on the Fitbit, applied a filter to show \texttt{Non-Wear}
  days, and removed all those days.
\item
  Verified column names and formats to ensure a seamless import into R.
\item
  Clean Data was then uploaded to R Studio with the same titles, and the
  inclusion of ``Cleaned'' was added to each file.
\end{itemize}

